What changed and why it fixes the freeze:
The gauge is registered once per name+tags. Micrometer caches it and calls its supplier on every Prometheus scrape. The supplier is h -> h.get().applyAsDouble(null) — it reads through the AtomicReference, so whatever function you last handed to registerOrUpdate is the one that runs on the next scrape. No remove. No gap. No race between scrape and re-registration.
One thing to check in your GaugeConfig: the cast assumes getFunction() returns something that can be invoked without an instance argument (the typical Solace SEMP case — your function closes over the queue/client it's reading). If getFunction() is Supplier<Number> or DoubleSupplier, adjust the holder type accordingly:
java// If getFunction() returns Supplier<Number>:
private final ConcurrentHashMap<String, AtomicReference<Supplier<Number>>> suppliers = ...;
Gauge.builder(metricName, holder, h -> h.get().get().doubleValue())

// If getFunction() returns DoubleSupplier:
private final ConcurrentHashMap<String, AtomicReference<DoubleSupplier>> suppliers = ...;
Gauge.builder(metricName, holder, h -> h.get().getAsDouble())
One catch worth being explicit about: if gaugeConfig.getFunction() itself closes over a stale reference (for example, it captured an old QueueInfo object from a previous SEMP poll), this pattern still goes stale — because you'd be swapping in a new closure each time, which works, but only if your refresh code is actually building a new GaugeConfig with a freshly-bound function each cycle. If instead the SEMP refresh updates fields on a long-lived object and getFunction() reads those fields, you don't even need the swap — the closure picks up the new values automatically. Worth tracing one gauge end-to-end to confirm where the staleness enters. The most common cause in Solace observability code is that the function captures a value (final long depth = info.getDepth()) instead of capturing the source (() -> info.getDepth()). If that's the bug, the supplier holder above masks it but the cleanest fix is in the function definition itself.
